{{Unreferenced|date=July 2009}} {{Infobox College baseball team |name = Boston College Eagles |founded = 1896 |logo = |logo_size = |university = Boston College |conference = Atlantic Coast Conference |conference_short = ACC |division = Atlantic |city = Chestnut Hill |stateabb = MA |state = Massachusetts |coach = Mike Gambino |tenure = 1st |stadium = [[Eddie Pellagrini Diamond at John Shea Field]] |capacity = 1,000 |nickname = [[Boston College Eagles|Eagles]] |color1 = Maroon |color2 = Gold |fontcolor = C5B358 |hex1 = 8B0000 |hex2 = C5B358 |national_champion = |cws = 1953, 1960, 1961, 1967 |ncaa_tourneys = 1949, 1953, 1955, 1960, 1961, 1967, 2009 |conference_tournament = |conference_champion = }} {{main|Boston College Eagles}} The '''[[Boston College Eagles|Boston College]] baseball team''' represents [[Boston College]] in [[NCAA]] [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] [[college baseball]]. The team participates in the Atlantic Division of the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]]. The head coach of the Eagles is Mike Gambino, a 2000 alumnus of Boston College, and the team plays its home games at [[Eddie Pellagrini Diamond at John Shea Field]].
==NCAA Division I tournament== The team has been selected to play in the [[NCAA Division I Baseball Championship|NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament]] seven times, most recently in [[2009 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament#Austin Super Regional|2009]]. It has played in the [[College World Series]] four times, the most recent being [[1967 College World Series|1967]].
==ACC tournament== {{main|ACC Baseball Tournament}}
==Longest game in college-baseball history== {{see also|Extra innings}} On May 30, 2009, the Eagles played in the longest game in college-baseball history â a 25-inning game â during the [[NCAA Division I Baseball Championship#Longest game in college baseball history|NCAA Division I Baseball Championship]] regional tournament at [[Austin, Texas]]. The [[Texas Longhorns|University of Texas Longhorns]] â who were designated the visiting team despite playing on their [[home advantage|home field]] â won, 3-2. The game lasted seven hours three minutes.<ref>*Schlegel, John. [http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090531&content_id=5064006&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb "Texas wins NCAA record 25-inning game"], MLB.com (MLB Advanced Media, L.P.), May 31, 2009. <!--accessed 2009-08-13--></ref><ref>[http://www.ncaa.com/brackets/2009/ncaa_bracket_DI_baseball.html "2009 NCAA Div. I Baseball College World Series Bracket"] ('''in column 1''' (Regionals), '''click on''' Austin box; '''then click on''' TexasâBC box). NCAA.com. <!--accessed 2009-08-13--></ref>
==Exhibition game with Boston Red Sox== ''See also [[spring training#Spring training locations by team|Spring training]]''. The team has played games with the [[Boston Red Sox]], as part of the Red Sox' [[spring training#Spring training locations by team|spring training]] (Grapefruit League) season. The current Red Sox spring-training stadium is [[City of Palms Park]], Fort Myers, Florida.
